    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-12-08T11:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-12-08T11:54:00-05:00" n="52"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                <head>52. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Mission at the United Nations</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d52fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 320.11/12–858. Confidential; Priority. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_HCF1">Hawley</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BRE3"
                            >Bacon</persName> on December 6; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                            >Kohler</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BRE3">Bacon</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_FCVJ1">Ferguson</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LJM3">Ludlow</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MGN1"
                            >Monsma</persName>, SEA, and NA; and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_WFO1">Wilcox</persName> who signed for Herter.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-12-08T11:54:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 8, 1958—11:54 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>528. Re: membership meeting. Despite considerations advanced <gloss
                        target="#t_DELGA1">Delga</gloss> 632,<note n="2" xml:id="d52fn2">
                        <gloss target="#t_DELGA1">Delga</gloss> 632, December 5, reported a general
                        reluctance among Security Council members to consider the question of
                        admitting Vietnam and Korea to the United Nations, advised the Department to
                        reconsider its instructions to introduce the matter, and outlined the
                        factors militating against such a move. (<hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>.,
                        320.11/12–558)</note> Mission should support renewed <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                        >SC</gloss> consideration of long-standing membership applications <gloss
                        target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> and Viet-Nam as instructed <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 516.<note n="3" xml:id="d52fn3">See <ref
                            target="#d48fn4">footnote 4, Document 48</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Not to do so, when <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> is meeting to consider
                    membership Guinea, would be construed as decreased interest our part to support
                    two well qualified states. Communist obstructive tactics should not deter <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> from making clear Communist responsibility this
                    impasse and continuing <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> interest welfare these
                    Free World governments. <pb facs="0117" n="87" xml:id="pg_87"/> Effect
                    sustaining morale <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> and Viet-Nam also
                    important considerations. Moreover, we have already undertaken in consultations
                    with them to support their applications.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
